post_text:
Wreaths Across America, an organization that honors fallen veterans, encouraged everyone to stand outside and wave a flag for one minute at 8:46, 9:03, 9:37 and 10:03 this morning in honor of those who died in the terrorist attacks of Sept. 11, 2001. Godwin Elementary teacher Danny Derden led the remembrance at the school with a moment of silence during the times when the planes crashed into the Twin Towers, the Pentagon and the field in Pennsylvania.

“I believe it is our duty as educators to remember our history and teach it,” said Mr. Derden, who is also a veteran. “I believe it is our duty as Americans to honor those who fell in these evil attacks.”

With research complete on kinematics, obstacle courses and scaled drawings, the Scientific Research and Design Engineering students at Princeton High School start construction on their American Ninja Warrior courses and learn to safely use a few shop tools in the process.

Luis Alejandro practices the adage of "Measure twice, cut once."

Draven Smith, Chase Leon, Wesley Baker and Tyler Brooks collaborate to solve design and construction problems.

Benjamin Herbst and Lucas Pereira mast the material styrofoam.

William Schroeder double checks his measurements before using a spade bit to create a recessed slot for a dowel.

Caleb Cooper, Jackson Phillips and Nicolas Marquez mold wire and cut PVC and wood for their obstacle course challenges.

Jayleen Tovar, Anthony Garcia and Mariah Cruz dive deep into the construction phase of their first obstacle course section.

In an effort to keep our parents, staff and community informed, Princeton ISD has created a COVID-19 Dashboard that will be updated weeky to reflect active lab-confirmed COVID-19 cases in Princeton ISD.

In addition to posting information on the website, campus-wide notification will be sent to both parents and staff when a lab-confirmed positive case has been reported at a campus.

Princeton ISD will personally contact individuals who may have come in close contact (as defined by TEA) with a lab-confirmed positive case on a campus. If you are NOT directly contacted, then you are NOT someone identified as having close contact with a positive individual.

The COVID-19 Dashboard is accessible from the main district website under the COVID-19 Operations tab and can be accessed below.

post_text:
As the families in southern Louisiana try to salvage their homes and surroundings by removing the clutter and trees so the utility companies can come in to restore power, it is estimated residents will remain without electricity and water for at least eight weeks.

A team from the PHS staff will make a trip to deliver needed items to the families. They will collect items in the PHS library until Friday, Sept. 11. NHS and Student Council will help in the effort to collect supplies.

Items needed include:
Plastic totes (they are using these to keep grocery items dry)
Duct tape
Water (single bottles or gallons)
Paper products/utensils (plates, bowls, napkins, forks, spoons)
Toilet paper
Trash bags
Canned vegetables
Canned soups
Dried beans
Rice
Gatorade
Granola bars
Peanut butter
Crackers
Bread
Shampoo

text:
As the families in southern Louisiana try to salvage their homes and surroundings by removing the clutter and trees so the utility companies can come in to restore power, it is estimated residents will remain without electricity and water for at least eight weeks.

A team from the PHS staff will make a trip to deliver needed items to the families. They will collect items in the PHS library until Friday, Sept. 11. NHS and Student Council will help in the effort to collect supplies.

Items needed include:
Plastic totes (they are using these to keep grocery items dry)
Duct tape
Water (single bottles or gallons)
Paper products/utensils (plates, bowls, napkins, forks, spoons)
Toilet paper
Trash bags
Canned vegetables
Canned soups
Dried beans
Rice
Gatorade
Granola bars
Peanut butter
Crackers
Bread
Shampoo
Soap

Blue shop towels

REMINDER: PISD will provide weekly curbside meal pick-up for remote learners starting today. This program is very different than the summer program, so read carefully.

MEAL PICK-UP PROCESS:
There will be three locations to choose from, Princeton High School, Southard Middle School or Harper Elementary. Pick up at one location for all of your remote learner students. Pick up will be 5-6 TONIGHT at the front of the schools.

Parents/guardians will need to show proof of PISD enrolment at pickup (student ID, report card, email from school stating the student is enrolled). THIS MUST BE SHOWN EVERY TIME YOU PICK UP THE MEAL.

MEAL COSTS AND PAYMENTS:
Meals will be charged to the student’s account according to the student’s eligibility status. There must be sufficient funds in a student’s meal account to cover the cost of the meals.

post_text: Southard principal Rich Boring had a message for his teaching staff today as they continue to plan for Thursday’s first day of school. Mr. Boring used his science background to encourage his staff to adopt the philosophy, “Be the Bean,” based on the book by the same name. The premise is that when faced with adversity, the coffee bean adapts and changes its surrounding environment for the better. To illustrate, he used beakers to show how a carrot, egg and coffee bean changed when submerged in boiling water. “You want to be an example for your students and show them how to be the bean when faced with problems in their lives,” Mr. Boring said.

Mr. Boring used his science background to encourage his staff to adopt the philosophy, “Be the Bean,” based on the book by the same name. The premise is that when faced with adversity, the coffee bean adapts and changes its surrounding environment for the better. To illustrate, he used beakers to show how a carrot, egg and coffee bean changed when submerged in boiling water. “You want to be an example for your students and show them how to be the bean when faced with problems in their lives,” Mr. Boring said.

Schedule information for PHS:

PHS counselors will release schedules for high school students through the Infinite Campus portal beginning tomorrow, Thursday, Aug. 6.

For students who may require a schedule change, use of the online Schedule Change Request Form is necessary to limit the amount of paper that is moved between individuals.

Click link for form using your Princeton ISD Google account.

Please understand that schedule requests may be subject to the following:

1) Schedule change requests are considered on a first-come, first-served basis. Requests will be considered, but are not guaranteed to be granted.

2) Changes are dependent on high school graduation requirements, available room in classes and the master schedule.

3) Dropping/adding courses could impact other class periods/teachers in your current schedule.

4) Student schedule changes will not be made for specific periods/teachers/lunches.

5) Athletics, band, choir, color guard, dance, cheer and ROTC changes will only be made after an email has been received from that coach/sponsor.

Starting Monday, July 13, Southard will have skills training for cross country athletes. With cross country being a sport many do along with football and volleyball, three different workouts will be offered.

If the athlete is only participating in CC and not doing FB or VB, skills will be Monday-Thursday from 6-7 a.m.

If the athlete is participating in both CC and FB, skills will be Tuesday and Thursday from 7-8 a.m.

If the athlete is participating in both CC and VB, skills will be Monday and Wednesday from 7-8 a.m.

It is very important these three groups of athletes maintain social distancing, so when the first group is leaving, it is very important the groups do not intermingle in any way. Athletes need to bring a mask with them so they have it available when they are in the campus building or not working out.

Athletes will be dropped off in the front of the school by the track and picked up at the back by the bus drop off line.

For questions, contact Coach Jack Perkins at jperkins@princetonisd.net.

post_text:
PISD was made aware this weekend that a Princeton ISD athletics staff member has tested positive for COVID-19. This individual was not at PISD facilities while exhibiting symptoms. Out of an abundance of caution, PISD is suspending all in-person athletic workouts until July 13 because of the UIL break the week after July 4.

Athletes and staff should remain vigilant in monitoring for symptoms from home for a period of two weeks from June 16 and ending June 30. Follow COVID-19 guidelines as outlined by the CDC.

Symptoms include:
Fever
Chills
Shortness of breath/difficulty breathing
Fatigue
Muscle or body aches
Headache
New loss of taste or smell
Sore throat
Congestion or runny nose
Nausea/vomiting
Diarrhea

If you have any questions or concerns regarding your child’s health, please reach out to their physician.

post_text:
All graduating seniors may pick up their diplomas and transcripts starting Monday, June 22, from 7:30 a.m.-noon and 1-4:30 p.m. Monday through Thursday.

If you have any outstanding balances in the district, those will need to be paid before you receive your diploma. If you still have a district Chromebook, please bring it as well. The replacement cost for a Chromebook is $210.

Congratulations again to those of you who were successful in completing your graduation requirements. We look forward to seeing you next week.

Clint Sadler
Principal
Princeton High School

post_text: Lowe Elementary, Princeton ISD’s newest school, hosted kindergarten graduation in the middle of the day as it started to heat up. Lowe kindergarten lead teacher Kim Anthony gives directions for the ceremony to Iker Gomez and his mom, Yuritzi Plancarte, and takes a quick photo with Kaiden Tommie. Jakobian Strawder was all decked out for graduation with his dad, Leonard Griffin. Princeton alum and Harper music teacher Kristen McClure makes sure all the kindergarten graduates make it to the jumbotron.

post_text:
The Princeton High School band is already preparing for graduation. More than 30 members of the band took turns recording the alma mater to be played at commencement on June 6. According to director Brandon Brewer, the students arrived at scheduled times over the course of two days and maintained social distancing to play the school song.

“We’ll be sending these recordings to a sound engineer, and he’ll put all
30+ tracks together,” Mr. Brewer said. “Once he is done, it will sound like all the instruments are playing together at the same time.”

About the photos:

Dylan Cook and Elizabeth Samples play their instruments in the sound room.

Mr. Brewer communicates with the band member recording inside the sound booth as Rayna Samples waits her turn.

Robby and Sarah Brewer rehearse with their instruments as Dillon Davis listens and checks them off the list.

post_text:
When the 2020 Princeton High School Winterguard season came to an abrupt end, the band staff thought there would be no other competitions for the guard this school year. However, that all changed when the North Texas Colorguard Association offered students a virtual solo competition.

The students had to choreograph their own solos and video themselves for the competition.

Princeton was represented in this contest by juniors Olivia Saari and Caroline Duncan and sophomore Madison Catenaccio. They each received a superior rating of 1.

Their instructor, Michael McGehee, and the rest of the band staff congratulates these students on a job well done and thanks them for going above and beyond to represent Princeton ISD and the rest of Panther Nation.

post_text:
Per Gov. Greg Abbott's executive order released today, which mandates school facilities remain closed for the rest of the 2019-2020 school year, Princeton ISD will continue with the home-based instruction currently in place.

Over the next few days, PISD administrators, in conjunction with the school board, will formulate a plan about how to conclude the school year and what that will look like.

Now that we know what the governor has mandated, the district has a lot of decisions to make, so watch for information to be sent out next week regarding any details necessary to finish out the current school year.

post_text: Weekly box meal distribution for anyone who qualifies for the free and reduced meal program will continue on Mondays at PHS. This box contains breakfast and lunch for the entire week, Monday-Friday. Distribution begins at 4 p.m. and continues until all boxes are distributed. This week 850 boxes were distributed, which represents 8,500 individual meals. This is an initiative the school board committed to when Princeton ISD moved to home-based instruction. It ensures children who normally had breakfast and lunch provided each day at school have enough food at home for the week.

Effective next Monday, April 13, Princeton ISD will alter its meal distribution in an effort to continue to reduce exposure to COVID-19 and comply with current shelter-in-place orders.

Breakfast and lunch for anyone 18 and younger will be distributed on Mondays and Wednesdays between 8-9 a.m. and 11:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m. Monday's meal sack will include breakfast and lunch for Monday and Tuesday. Wednesday's meal sack will include breakfast and lunch for Wednesday, Thursday and Friday.

post_text:
Princeton High School is making every attempt to hold graduation commencement as scheduled, which is 7 p.m. Thursday, May 28, at Allen Event Center. However, with the current state of the country as it deals with the pandemic, these decisions are not in the district's hands as PISD must adhere to all local, county and state orders in an attempt to keep our community healthy and safe from further spread of COVID-19.

"We know parents and graduates are anxious to know plans for this year's commencement, and we want to honor the Class of 2020 and plan to do so when and where we are allowed," Superintendent Philip Anthony said. "We just can't say for certain when or where at this time as it is out of our control."

Some school districts have already canceled, postponed or rescheduled their graduation ceremonies, however, PISD school administrators do not want to make premature decisions without knowing if they will be necessary.

Princeton ISD will communicate graduation plans as soon as there is enough information to make a decision.

According to representatives of Balfour, all graduation items previously ordered will be sent to the students' homes, except for caps and gowns. Balfour's plan originally was to deliver caps and gowns by hand to PHS in late April. However, since schools are closed until at least May 4, Balfour plans to reassess at that time because their plant is currently shut down.

Representatives of Balfour assure the PHS seniors they will have their caps and gowns in time for graduation, but these unique circumstances are forcing unprecedented measures.

post_text:
Princeton ISD teachers are still in the process of personally contacting the parent of every student, which is a monumental task.

Although the district has reached roughly 85 percent, there are still some contacts to be made. Continue to expect a call.

However, if you would like to initiate contact in the normal format you would reach out to your child's teacher, feel free to do so.

For elementary, it would be the child's homeroom teacher.

For middle school, it would be the 4th-period teacher.

For PHS, it is their Pride Time teacher.

Anticipate later today or early Thursday an email with information on pickup procedures for instructional packets and food service beginning Monday, March 23.

Because of the Centers for Disease Control guidance to avoid large gatherings, the Lois Nelson Public Library has decided to close the library as well as suspend all programming and meeting room usage until March 23.
This decision is out of an abundance of caution and consideration of our community health. You can monitor the city’s website for up-to-date developments for future library programs such as Facebook Live story times. In addition, there are many online e-books, audiobooks and streaming videos available through Overdrive https://princeton.biblionix.com/catalog/ which is a free service.

post_text:
Princeton competed at the Yellow Rose District of the National Speech and Debate Association. At this tournament, students compete for three grueling days to take one of the elite spots in each event at nationals in Albuquerque, N.M. June 14-19. There, they compete with the other elite students from the 111 other districts throughout the nation and a couple international programs.

Several students make it deep into outrounds at the tournament, including Jasmyn Batley and Natalie Self in CX Debate, Casey Angell, Eden Burke, Taylor Dougherty and Vivian Long in Congressional Debate and Casey Angell, Eden Burke, Vivian Long and Hannah Rodriguez in Extemporaneous Speaking.

After all the dust cleared, the following four students qualified for nationals at this time:

Casey Angell in LD Debate
Eden Burke in Extemp Speaking
The team of Hannah Rodriguez and Vivian Long in CX Debate

post_text:
The applications for the Princeton Ministerial Alliance scholarships are available in the counseling office with Hope Dixon. There will be two $500 scholarships awarded and will require the student read a simple leadership book, fill out the application form and write a brief 150-word essay. The due date will be Monday, March 31, in the counseling office.

The Princeton Ministerial Alliance will have a committee look over the applications and choose from the qualifying students. Scholarships will be awarded at the baccalaureate Sunday, May 24.

post_text:
The PHS volleyball program will organize youth volleyball teams to compete in Allen this spring. For parents interested in volunteer coaching, facilities and gym space in Princeton will be available for practices. Princeton volleyball will also host Saturday volleyball clinics in March, April and May.

The goal is to help girls develop a volleyball base on which to grow and give them the experience to better prepare them for competition in junior high and beyond.

For more information, contact Coach Kathryn Hancock at khancock@princetonisd.net.

post_text: The CX debate team competed in likely the hardest UIL CX district in Texas. Hannah Rodriguez and Vivian Long secured 2nd place and will advance to state. Taylor Dougherty and Eden Long lost on a 2-1 decision to the 2019 State Champions to get 3rd place and alternate to state. Taylor was awarded "Top Speaker" for the district. Novice CXers Jasmine Batley, Natalie Self, Robert Arroyo and Paola Diaz held their own but were unable to advance to semifinals, consisting of two Lovejoy teams competing against two Princeton teams. The judges deciding the semifinals rounds, which determine the two teams who advance to state, said they easily could have been judging finals at state.

post_text: A Princeton ISD bus carrying students to Lowe Elementary was involved in a minor accident this morning. Bus No. 11 was rear-ended near the intersection of FM 982 and County Road 447 by the ag barn. It appears three students may have minor injuries, and their parents have been contacted. The remaining 16 students were transferred to another bus and taken to school. Officials are in the process of notifying those parents now.

post_text: The first six weeks at Godwin marked the very first "Sportsmanship Award" presented by Coach Katherine High. To earn this award, students write their names on the board representing their own judgment of important sportsmanship traits like integrity, loyalty and work ethic. At the end of each six weeks, the student with the most signatures on the board earns the Sportsmanship Award certificate for the six weeks and the rights to keep the grade level trophy in their classroom. At the end of the year, the student who wins the award overall, gets to keep the trophy. The first winner in 5th grade was Jackson Passons.

To earn this award, students write their names on the board representing their own judgment of important sportsmanship traits like integrity, loyalty and work ethic. At the end of each six weeks, the student with the most signatures on the board earns the Sportsmanship Award certificate for the six weeks and the rights to keep the grade level trophy in their classroom. At the end of the year, the student who wins the award overall, gets to keep the trophy. The first winner in 5th grade was Jackson Passons.
